# Manage Superpowers Whitelist

> **Scope**: Codex on Windows only. The supporting scripts use Windows junctions
> and PowerShell. The skill is gated to `harness=codex` + `os=windows` in
> `manifests/default.yaml`. Do not install on macOS / Linux.

## Overview

Use the local manager scripts instead of editing links or `AGENTS.md` by hand. The non-interactive PowerShell entrypoint is the source of truth for agent-driven changes; the batch file and desktop shortcut are convenience launchers for human use.

## Core Commands

### List current state

Run:

```powershell
powershell -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File ${WORKSPACE_ROOT}\.codex\scripts\manage-superpowers.ps1 -ListOnly
```

Use this when the user asks which superpowers skills are currently enabled.

### Set the whitelist

Run the PowerShell script with the full desired enabled set:

```powershell
powershell -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File ${WORKSPACE_ROOT}\.codex\scripts\manage-superpowers.ps1 -SetEnabled brainstorming
```

For multiple skills, pass them as separate values:

```powershell
powershell -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File ${WORKSPACE_ROOT}\.codex\scripts\manage-superpowers.ps1 -SetEnabled brainstorming systematic-debugging writing-plans
```

Always pass the complete desired whitelist, not just incremental additions. The script removes no-longer-enabled links, creates missing junctions, and rewrites the managed whitelist block in `${USERPROFILE}\.codex\AGENTS.md`.

### Launch the interactive picker

For a user-facing picker, run:

```powershell
${WORKSPACE_ROOT}\.codex\scripts\manage-superpowers.bat
```

The picker uses `Up/Down` to move, `Space` to toggle, `S` to save, and `Q` to exit.

### Recreate the desktop shortcut

If the user wants the double-click launcher restored, run:

```powershell
$desktop = Join-Path $env:USERPROFILE 'Desktop'
$shortcutPath = Join-Path $desktop 'Superpowers Skills Manager.lnk'
$targetPath = '${WORKSPACE_ROOT}\.codex\scripts\manage-superpowers.bat'
$workingDir = '${WORKSPACE_ROOT}\.codex\scripts'
$wsh = New-Object -ComObject WScript.Shell
$shortcut = $wsh.CreateShortcut($shortcutPath)
$shortcut.TargetPath = $targetPath
$shortcut.WorkingDirectory = $workingDir
$shortcut.Description = 'Manage enabled superpowers skills for Codex'
$shortcut.IconLocation = "$env:SystemRoot\System32\shell32.dll,21"
$shortcut.Save()
```

Writing the shortcut usually requires escalated permission in this environment because it targets the user desktop outside `${WORKSPACE_ROOT}`.

## Managed Surfaces

Treat these as one managed set:

- `${USERPROFILE}\.codex\superpowers\skills` is the source library
- `${USERPROFILE}\.agents\skills\superpowers` exposes only enabled skills as junctions
- `${USERPROFILE}\.codex\AGENTS.md` contains the managed whitelist block and activation policy
- `${USERPROFILE}\Desktop\Superpowers Skills Manager.lnk` is the optional shortcut

Do not manually edit only one surface unless the script is unavailable.

## Verification

After changing the whitelist:

- Confirm the script output lists the intended enabled skills
- Confirm `${USERPROFILE}\.agents\skills\superpowers` contains only the enabled skill links
- Confirm the managed block in `${USERPROFILE}\.codex\AGENTS.md` matches the same set
- Tell the user to restart Codex before expecting the new whitelist to apply
